Exploring the Future of Consumption: Caribbean perspective on the 6th China International Consumer Products Expo
By Jasveer Seecharan
April 25, 2026

A Premier Global Event for Consumer Goods
The China International Consumer Products Expo (CICPE) is the nation’s only national‑level exhibition dedicated to consumer goods and the largest event of its kind in the Asia‑Pacific region. It serves not only as a showcase for domestic and international products but also as a vital platform for China to demonstrate its commitment to global openness.

The 6th CICPE took place from April 13 to 18 in Hainan, China. With a focus on premium, new, unique, and specialty products, the expo brought together high‑quality consumer goods resources from around the world, along with global buyers and sellers. Highlights included global product launches, debut showcases, an international fashion week, and other related events.

My Visit – April 17, 2026
I attended the expo on April 17, following a route that began in Hall 5, then proceeded to Hall 4, Hall 1, and finally Halls 6 and 7.

Hall 5 – Luxury Meets Technology
We started in Hall 5, where we viewed automotive exhibits from Huawei, Audi, and Bentley. These luxury brands clearly demonstrated how premium consumption is increasingly integrated with cutting‑edge technology — from intelligent cockpits to electric mobility solutions.

Hall 4 – International Pavilions
Moving to Hall 4, we explored various country pavilions:

Hong Kong – Served shrimp and lemon tea.

Thailand – Offered tea and coffee.

Malaysia – Provided samples of local beverages.

Mongolia – Impressed visitors with beautiful cashmere sweaters.

A particularly memorable stop was an Indonesian paper company that produces everyday items such as fast‑food takeout boxes. This was a real‑world example of how global supply chains deliver sustainable, daily‑use products to consumers worldwide.

Hall 1 – Technology Consumption Zone
In Hall 1, we encountered robots, virtual reality experiences, and various health tech and AI‑driven consumer solutions. I spoke with a representative from EY, who introduced me to ESG.ai — a data‑driven analytical tool that will be highly valuable for my future research as an MBA student and data analyst.

Halls 6 & 7 – Trends in Health & Digital Retail
Throughout most booths across the expo, there were numerous promotions for vitamins and skincare products. Many brands were actively livestreaming their product demonstrations, highlighting how physical retail and digital engagement have become seamlessly integrated in China’s consumer market.

Key Takeaways
The CICPE is more than a trade show — it is a living laboratory for consumer trends, technology, and sustainability. From luxury cars to cashmere sweaters, from shrimp and lemon tea to AI‑driven health solutions, and from paper takeout boxes to livestream sellers, the expo offered concrete, real‑world evidence of how brands use technology and events to drive consumption.

For any MBA student or researcher, attending CICPE provides:

Practical tools like ESG.ai

Real‑time observations of global supply chains

Deep insights into the future of consumption — what we buy, and why


